I've reviewed the implementation. Here's my assessment from the HTML/CSS perspective:

## What looks good

1. **Semantic HTML**: Using `<a>` elements for navigation links -- correct. These navigate to new pages, so links are the right element.
2. **Route handler logic**: The session check + redirect pattern is clean and keeps the template simple (no authenticated state needed in the template).
3. **Tests**: The two new tests cover the right behavioral assertions -- link presence for unauthenticated, redirect for authenticated. The test helpers are well-structured.
4. **Copy**: "Keep track of what you need to do." is an improvement -- more action-oriented, less happy talk.

## Issues to address

### 1. Missing CSS for `.btn` and `.btn--primary` / `.btn--secondary` (blocking)

The template uses `class="btn btn--primary"` and `class="btn btn--secondary"`, but **no `.btn` styles exist in `main.css`**. These links will render as plain text links with no button styling. The CTA will look identical to the secondary link -- no visual hierarchy.

You need to either:
- **(a)** Add `.btn` component styles to the components layer in `main.css`, or
- **(b)** Switch to the approach I suggested earlier -- use a `.landing__cta` class for the primary link (styled as a button) and leave "Sign in" as a plain `<a>` (which already has blue underlined styling from the base layer).

I'd recommend option (b) because it's scoped to this component and avoids introducing a generic `.btn` abstraction prematurely. We can extract `.btn` later if the pattern is reused. Here's what the CSS would look like:

```css
/* ---- Landing Page ---- */
.landing {
    text-align: center;
    padding-block-start: var(--space-3xl);
}

.landing h1 {
    margin-block-end: var(--space-sm);
}

.landing p {
    color: var(--color-fg-muted);
    margin-block-end: var(--space-xl);
}

.landing__actions {
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    align-items: center;
    gap: var(--space-md);
}

.landing__cta {
    display: inline-flex;
    align-items: center;
    justify-content: center;
    padding-block: var(--space-sm);
    padding-inline: var(--space-xl);
    background-color: var(--color-primary);
    color: white;
    text-decoration: none;
    border-radius: var(--radius-md);
    font-weight: var(--font-medium);
}

.landing__cta:hover {
    background-color: var(--color-primary-dark);
    color: white;
}
```

And the template would become:
```html
<div class="landing">
    <h1>Welcome</h1>
    <p>Keep track of what you need to do.</p>
    <div class="landing__actions">
        <a href="/register" class="landing__cta">Create account</a>
        <a href="/login">Sign in</a>
    </div>
</div>
```

### 2. `<nav>` element semantics (minor, non-blocking)

The template wraps the links in `<nav aria-label="Get started">`. This is technically fine -- navigation links in a `<nav>` is semantically valid. However, this creates a **second `<nav>` landmark** on the page (the base template already has `<nav aria-label="Main navigation">` in the header). Two nav landmarks is acceptable when they have distinct labels, and yours does ("Get started" vs "Main navigation"), so this is defensible.

